2002-08-25  Seth Robertson  <seth@winwood.sysdetect.com>

	* Make.*: Many many performance changes [make overhead now cut to
	4/5ths of previous level] and normalization to normal make
	standards where there was a bizarre reassignment [PWD/CURDIR].

	* Make.include: Exerpt BK_USER_VARIABLE discovery to
	Make.bkvariables.  Move inclusion of file until after it
	is defined.

	* Make.production: CURDIR->PWD changes.

	* Make.variables: Add protected area which only runs one per make
	invocation instead of once per directory.  In this area, set
	${PWD} to be normalized so that self and all descendants get clean
	path.  Obviously perform PWD->PWDPROG and CURDIR->PWD changes.
	Set BK_INSTALLRDIR and BK_INSTALLPATH once for everyone [and have
	them use ${PWD} instead of `${PWDPROG}`]

	* Make.config.in (PWDPROG): Make by default uses ${PWD} to mean
	same as shell does.  Thus, for better compatability we should
	rename path-to-pwd-program to ${PWDPROG}.  Not that I see any
	reason why you need to use it, given ${PWD}.

	* Make.targets: Implement PWD->PWDPROG and CURDIR->PWD changes as
	described elsewhere.

	* Make.bkvariables (BK_USER_VARIABLES): Performance: search for
	.user-variables only once.  Afterwards, as we decend, check to see
	if CWD has file.  If it does, set and use for self and descendants.

